/**
 * @page map_authoring_guide How To Add A Map
 * @tableofcontents
 *
 * @section map_authoring_files Files To Touch
 *
 * Adding a map usually means editing:
 * - a `.map` file under `assets/data/maps/`
 * - one or two background images under `assets/tilesets/`
 * - optional NPC dialogue and party entries inside the map file itself
 *
 * For a visual workflow, run `python3 tools/map_editor.py` from the repository root.
 * The editor can paint tile rows, pick background and overlay images, and place
 * warp and NPC coordinates directly on the map.
 *
 * The runtime parser is documented in @ref MapFormat.
 *
 * @section map_authoring_sections Required Sections
 *
 * A map file normally contains:
 * - `[header]` with `id`, `width`, `height`, and background paths
 * - `[tiles]` with one character per tile
 * - optional `[warps]`
 * - optional `[encounters]`
 * - optional `[npcs]`
 *
 * Example:
 * @code{.ini}
 * [header]
 * id|example_map
 * width|8
 * height|6
 * background|assets/tilesets/example/maps/example.png
 *
 * [tiles]
 * ########
 * #......#
 * #..TT..#
 * #...d..#
 * #......#
 * ########
 *
 * [warps]
 * 4|3|player_house_1f|4|8
 * @endcode
 *
 * @section map_authoring_npcs NPC Entries
 *
 * NPC rows use the format:
 * @code{.txt}
 * id|name|type|x|y|facing|sightRange|dialogue|sprite|party
 * @endcode
 *
 * Notes:
 * - Dialogue lines are separated by `;`
 * - Dialogue stages are separated by `@@`
 * - Trainer party entries use `speciesId:level`
 * - The sprite field can include `@hidden` to start hidden
 *
 * @section map_authoring_checks Validation
 *
 * Before considering a map done:
 * - Build and run the game and walk the whole map.
 * - Verify every door/warp target exists.
 * - Verify tall grass and encounter areas behave as expected.
 * - Verify NPC dialogue, facing, and trainer sight ranges.
 * - Run the map-format and world-generation tests.
 *
 * The existing `assets/data/maps/pallet_town/pallet_town.map` file is a good
 * reference for a complete overworld map.
 */
